  "prompt": "Why does a concussion cause someone to throw up?",
  "response": "A concussion can cause vomiting due to several factors related to brain injury and disruption of normal brain function:\n\n1. Brain Inflammation\n- The brain becomes swollen and irritated\n- This inflammation can affect the vestibular system and areas controlling balance\n\n2. Disruption of Neural Signals\n- The brain's normal signaling pathways are temporarily interrupted\n- This can cause miscommunication between the brain and body systems\n\n3. Vestibular Disturbance\n- The concussion impacts the inner ear and balance centers\n- This can lead to dizziness, vertigo, and nausea\n- Similar to motion sickness, these sensations can trigger vomiting\n\n4. Increased Intracranial Pressure\n- Brain swelling can increase pressure inside the skull\n- This pressure can stimulate the brain's vomiting center\n\n5. Autonomic Nervous System Disruption\n- The concussion can affect the autonomic nervous system\n- This can cause involuntary responses like nausea and vomiting\n\nVomiting after a concussion can be a sign of a serious brain injury, so medical attention is recommended if someone experiences repeated or persistent vomiting following a head injury.",
